description.narrative: (Georgia): Hazelnuts are a key cash crop in Georgia, providing livelihoods directly to some 50,000 growers and processors. The Georgia Hazelnut Improvement Project (G-HIP) is a partnership between USAID and Ferrero SpA, representing the overlapping interests of the private sector's commercial activities with USAID's developmental goals. G-HIP is transforming the hazelnut value chain, leveraging expertise and financial support from the private and public sectors to improve hazelnut production and post-harvest handling practices and infrastructure while providing better incomes and employment for rural farmers. G-HIP incentivizes farmers to produce high-quality hazelnuts to generate more income and promote USAID/Georgia's CDCS DO3: Inclusive high-value employment opportunities provided through increased economic growth (JRS 2.3). G-HIP promotes Georgia's self-reliance by pooling more than $6 million in public and private resources in support of hazelnut sector (JRS 5.2.1, JSP 3.3) and will provide $350,000 in training and technical assistance to help protect livelihoods of 50,000 vulnerable farmers living near the occupied territory of Abkhazia and promote hazelnut exports to the EU, thereby reducing Georgia's susceptibility to Kremlin pressure (CAATSA Goal 8.) G-HIP targets 20,000 smallholder farmers and 30 hazelnut processors. Technical assistance will build the capacity of local organizations to provide extension and consulting services to their members and reduce reliance on external donors, while building the capacity of the private sector to produce and process higher quality, more valuable hazelnuts. It will continue to co-invest in high tech processing equipment, such as huskers and dryers, to support these goals. G-HIP will continue to modernize the Georgian hazelnut sector with a focus on traceability and quality-based pricing systems. USAID plans to transition out of the hazelnut sector by the end of the 2020-2025 CDCS strategy period..
